text: I'm normally not one to cry "The original was better" but I think I have to do it here. What makes the original Seven Samurai and its western remake Magnificent Seven so good is how it's a human story of outlaws seeking redemption. Not to mention the original was much more focused on tension. The only thing each of them had was a bullet for defense, and they could die rather easily (as some of them did). But here, they have them performing superhuman feats of speed and marksmanship while explosions ring out around them. That's not tense. That has no depth. All it is brainless action, and the original films were anything but brainless.

text: Antoine Fuqua doesn't seem like the right choice at all the be helming a remake of one of MGM's most iconic films. Plus I'm not a big fan of most of the writers they brought on for this one, except for Nic Pizzolatto. Overall though, I think MGM put the wrong people in charge of this remake and at least for me, the trailer shows how this movie is going to be lacking in comparison to the 1960 version of the film.  Plus I'm not a big fan of them trying to diversify the cast for the sake of political correctness. It's not really necessary for the sort of movie they're remaking. On the bright side though, it looks a hell of a lot better than the Ben Hur remake that's also getting released.

text: For those with questions, concerns or problems with the "multicultural" look of the film, I found the following on Wikipedia:  "Census records suggest that about 15% of all cowboys were of African-American ancestry—ranging from about 25% on the trail drives out of Texas, to very few in the northwest. Similarly, cowboys of Mexican descent also averaged about 15% of the total, but were more common in Texas and the southwest. Other estimates suggest that in the late 19th century, one out of every three cowboys was a Mexican vaquero, and 20% may have been African-American."  I'm guessing the Asian cowguy is there for the Chinese box office, not historical accuracy or high-minded ideals. Nothing wrong with that either way.

text: I don't see why this had to be remade, and while I appreciate a more diverse group of heroes why move the town so far north? We've gone from a Mexican town to an (apparently exclusively white) American one. Politically incredibly stupid given how very much aware people are of whitewashing nowadays. A border town with a mixed population, fine (especially as that allows for either conversations about racism or deconstruction of modern ideas of same). Changing the villains from Mexican Banditos to a mixed group including displaced Confederates (given that several of your white hat gunslingers would also likely be former Confederate soldiers and allow for conversations there), maybe making them Comancheros, fine. But this is just asking for fallout.

text: MGM today is so very predictable,that it just isn't the same studio it used to be,even after allowing Ted Turner to buy their birthright in 1985,just look at the mess this studio's in! even after recovering from their Chapter 11 some six or more years ago,the studio,owned by a group of Financial investors,including SONY,is just anything today,but what it once used to be-and THIS is all they can do,,remake their classic Movie and TV library-pathetic! "THE MAGNIFICENT SEVEN" was released by United Artists in 1960,and became a popular franchise for UA and The Mirisch Corporation-so whatever MGM is thinking today,trying to do another remake from it's MGM/UA library will be another costly disaster,added to the list of all their previous disasters,with their financial partnership with SONY-and if director Antoine Fuqua thinks he can do a better job then the original 1960 version,then he'll need all the luck in the world! Gary Barber has some interesting ideas,but trying to run MGM the way he's doing it,isn't impressive or successful,despite some minor successes in the past five years,or the studio's arrangements to depend on SONY and Warner Bros. as financial partners,is just so pathetic! Fuqua recently directed Denzel Washington in SONY/Columbia's remake of TV's "THE EQUALIZER",,and that was as pathetic as it got! nobody in this business has talent,taste,or class anymore-and for a once major studio like MGM to fall this low,has to suck seriously!! good luck,trying to mine gold with MGM's current moviemaking!
